README.md
     9‚Üí# Mitt
    10‚Üí
    11‚Üí> Tiny 200b functional event emitter / pubsub.
    12‚Üí
    13‚Üí-   **Microscopic:** weighs less than 200 bytes gzipped
    14‚Üí-   **Useful:** a wildcard `"*"` event type listens to all events
    15‚Üí-   **Familiar:** same names & ideas as [Node's EventEmitter](https://nodejs.org/api/events.html#events_class_eventemitter)
    16‚Üí-   **Functional:** methods don't rely on `this`
    17‚Üí-   **Great Name:** somehow [mitt](https://npm.im/mitt) wasn't taken
    18‚Üí
    19‚ÜíMitt was made for the browser, but works in any JavaScript runtime. It has no dependencies and supports IE9+.
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí## Table of Contents
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üí-   [Install](#install)
    24‚Üí-   [Usage](#usage)
    25‚Üí-   [Examples & Demos](#examples--demos)
    26‚Üí-   [API](#api)
    27‚Üí-   [Contribute](#contribute)
    28‚Üí-   [License](#license)
    29‚Üí
    30‚Üí## Install
    31‚Üí
    32‚ÜíThis project uses [node](http://nodejs.org) and [npm](https://npmjs.com). Go check them out if you don't have them locally installed.
    33‚Üí
    34‚Üí```sh
    35‚Üí$ npm install --save mitt
    36‚Üí```
    37‚Üí
    38‚ÜíThen with a module bundler like [rollup](http://rollupjs.org/) or [webpack](https://webpack.js.org/), use as you would anything else:
    39‚Üí
    40‚Üí```javascript
    41‚Üí// using ES6 modules
    42‚Üíimport mitt from 'mitt'
    43‚Üí
    44‚Üí// using CommonJS modules
    45‚Üívar mitt = require('mitt')
    46‚Üí```
    47‚Üí
    48‚ÜíThe [UMD](https://github.com/umdjs/umd) build is also available on [unpkg](https://unpkg.com):
    49‚Üí
    50‚Üí```html
    51‚Üí<script src="https://unpkg.com/mitt/dist/mitt.umd.js"></script>
    52‚Üí```
    53‚Üí
    54‚ÜíYou can find the library on `window.mitt`.
    55‚Üí
    56‚Üí## Usage
    57‚Üí
    58‚Üí```js
    59‚Üíimport mitt from 'mitt'
    60‚Üí
    61‚Üíconst emitter = mitt()
    62‚Üí
    63‚Üí// listen to an event
    64‚Üíemitter.on('foo', e => console.log('foo', e) )
    65‚Üí
    66‚Üí// listen to all events
    67‚Üíemitter.on('*', (type, e) => console.log(type, e) )
    68‚Üí
    69‚Üí// fire an event
    70‚Üíemitter.emit('foo', { a: 'b' })
    71‚Üí
    72‚Üí// clearing all events
    73‚Üíemitter.all.clear()
    74‚Üí
    75‚Üí// working with handler references:
    76‚Üífunction onFoo() {}
    77‚Üíemitter.on('foo', onFoo)   // listen
    78‚Üíemitter.off('foo', onFoo)  // unlisten
    79‚Üí```
    80‚Üí
    81‚Üí### Typescript
    82‚Üí
    83‚ÜíSet `"strict": true` in your tsconfig.json to get improved type inference for `mitt` instance methods.
    84‚Üí
    85‚Üí```ts
    86‚Üíimport mitt from 'mitt';
    87‚Üí
    88‚Üítype Events = {
    89‚Üí  foo: string;
    90‚Üí  bar?: number;
    91‚Üí};
    92‚Üí
    93‚Üíconst emitter = mitt<Events>(); // inferred as Emitter<Events>
    94‚Üí
    95‚Üíemitter.on('foo', (e) => {}); // 'e' has inferred type 'string'
    96‚Üí
    97‚Üíemitter.emit('foo', 42); // Error: Argument of type 'number' is not assignable to parameter of type 'string'. (2345)
    98‚Üí```
    99‚Üí
   100‚ÜíAlternatively, you can use the provided `Emitter` type:
   101‚Üí
   102‚Üí```ts
   103‚Üíimport mitt, { Emitter } from 'mitt';
   104‚Üí
   105‚Üítype Events = {
   106‚Üí  foo: string;
   107‚Üí  bar?: number;
   108‚Üí};
   109‚Üí
   110‚Üíconst emitter: Emitter<Events> = mitt<Events>();
   111‚Üí```
   112‚Üí
